  "text": "Following [CITATION_1] , we can investigate, in the more general context of the nth-order utility premium, how this measure reacts to the introduction on wealth of a sure loss ( l with l > 0) or a zero-mean background risk (~ with E(~ ) = 0). As intuition suggests, the pain increases in both cases under usual conditions on the signs of higher-order derivatives of the utility function. Indeed, considering the impact of a sure loss and a background risk on the nth-order utility premium, we obtain:",
